\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. C. argentea} L., {\i Sp. Pl}. 205 (1753). Glabrous, branched annual 15-50 cm. Leaves broadly lanceolate to ovate; petioles short. Inflorescences subsessile, spicate, usually cylindrical, often fasciated. Flowers sessile; perianth much longer than the bracteoles, usually purple, sometimes red, orange, yellow or white.{\i  Widely cultivated for ornament, and frequently occurring as a casual in S. Europe}.[It.] ({\i Tropics}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 The plant cultivated in Europe is var. {\i cristata} (L.) O. Kuntze ({\i C. cristata }L.).
